SUBSTITUTE FOR
HOUSE BILL NO. 4864
A bill to amend 1978 PA 368, entitled
"Public health code,"
by amending section 5456 (MCL 333.5456), as amended by 2002 PA 644.
THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF MICHIGAN ENACT:
1 Sec. 5456. (1) "Department" means the department of community
2 health.
3 (1) (2) "Deteriorated paint" means paint or other surface
4 coating that is cracking, flaking, chipping, peeling, or otherwise
5 damaged or separating from the substrate of a building component.
6 (2) (3) "Discipline" means 1 of the specific types or
7 categories of lead-based paint activities identified in this part
8 for which an individual may receive training from an accredited
9 training program and become certified by the department.
EMR H01021'25 (H-1) jmwtgd

2
1 (3) (4) "Distinct painting history" means the application
2 history, as indicated by its visual appearance or a record of
3 application, over time of paint or other surface coatings to a
4 component or room.
5 (4) (5) "Documented methodology" means a method or protocol
6 used to do either or both of the following:
7 (a) Sample and test for the presence of lead in paint, dust,
8 and soil.
9 (b) Perform related work practices as described in rules
10 promulgated under this part.
11 (5) (6) "Dust lead hazard" means surface dust in a residential
12 dwelling or child occupied facility that contains a concentration
13 of lead at or in excess of levels identified by the EPA pursuant to
14 section 403 of title IV of the toxic substances control act, Public
15 Law 94-469, 15 U.S.C. USC 2683, or as otherwise defined by rule.
16 (6) (7) "Elevated blood lead level" or "EBL" means for
17 purposes of lead abatement an excessive absorption of lead that is
18 a confirmed concentration of lead in whole blood of 20 ug/dl,
19 micrograms of lead per deciliter of whole blood, for a single
20 venous test or of 15-19 ug/dl in 2 consecutive tests taken 3 to 4
21 months apart. For purposes of case management of children 6 years
22 of age or less, elevated blood level means an excessive absorption
23 of lead that is a confirmed concentration of lead in whole blood of
24 10 ug/dl.the lowest of the following:
25 (a) A concentration of lead in whole blood that is equal to or
26 greater than 3.5 micrograms per deciliter.
27 (b) A concentration of lead in whole blood that is equal to or
28 greater than the blood lead reference value for children, as
29 determined by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
EMR H01021'25 (H-1) jmwtgd

3
1 (7) (8) "Encapsulant" means a substance that forms a barrier
2 between lead-based paint and the environment using a liquid-applied
3 coating, with or without reinforcement materials, or an adhesively
4 bonded covering material.
5 (8) (9) "Encapsulation" means the application of an
6 encapsulant.
7 (9) (10) "Enclosure" means the use of rigid, durable
8 construction materials that are mechanically fastened to the
9 substrate in order to act as a barrier between lead-based paint and
10 the environment.
11 (10) (11) "EPA" means the United States environmental
12 protection agency.Environmental Protection Agency.
